        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/hawaiiCoup.jpg'),
        description: `On this day in 1893, a U.S.-backed coup d'état against Queen Lili'uokalani took place, establishing the Republic of Hawaii and beginning the process of U.S. annexation. The majority of the insurgents were non-natives, and they successfully requested assistance from the U.S. government, who sent 162 sailors to occupy Oahu.\n\nAlthough the revolutionaries established an independent republic, it was with the ultimate goal of the United States annexing the islands, which occurred in 1898.\n\nThis revolution and the subsequent annexation of Hawaii marked a new era of expansionism from the United States. The same year, the U.S. fought and won the Spanish-American War, acquiring Puerto Rico, Guam, the Philippines, and establishing economic control of Cuba via the Platt Amendment.\n\nIn 1993, the U.S. government issued an "Apology Resolution", acknowledging that "the overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii occurred with the active participation of agents and citizens of the United States and further acknowledges that the Native Hawaiian people never directly relinquished to the United States their claims to their inherent sovereignty as a people over their national lands".`,
