        title: 'Samuel Gompers (1850 - 1924)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Individuals/samuelGompers.jpg'),
        description: `Samuel Gompers, born on this day in 1850, was the founder of the American Federation of Labor, serving as the organization's president almost without interruption from 1886 until his death in 1924. He promoted collaboration among the different craft unions that comprised the AFL and supported collective bargaining to secure shorter hours and higher wages for laborers.\n\nAlthough Gompers began his career sympathetic to socialist and Georgist thought, he became increasingly conservative throughout his career, making "peace" with capitalist labor relations rather than seeking to abolish them. This led to a split in the labor movement, with the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW) representing the more radical advocation of labor interests via industrial unionism.\n\nGompers successfully advocated for anti-immigrant and anti-socialist politics with the AFL's influence, supporting the Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 and the Spanish-Civil War, and cooperating with widespread government arrests of union leaders for the IWW's militant opposition to World War I.`,
        link: 'https://aflcio.org/about/history/labor-history-people/samuel-gompers',
