        title: 'Langston Hughes (1901 - 1967)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Individuals/langstonHughes.jpg'),
        description: `James Langston Hughes, born on this day in 1901, was an American author and social activist best known for being a luminary of the Harlem Renaissance. He moved from Joplin, Missouri to New York City as a young man, where he made his career. One of the earliest innovators of the then-new literary art form called jazz poetry.\n\nHughes was a communist sympathizer - his poetry was frequently published in the CPUSA newspaper and he was involved in initiatives supported by Communist organizations, such as the drive to free the Scottsboro Boys, a group of black teens falsely accused of rape. During the Spanish Civil War, Hughes traveled there as a correspondent for the Baltimore Afro-American.\n\nAfter being compelled to testify for a Senate Committee led by Joseph McCarthy, Hughes distanced himself from leftist politics, saying "[My not joining the Communist Party] was based on strict discipline and the acceptance of directives that I, as a writer, did not wish to accept."`,
