        title: 'Colonial Building Riot (1932)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/colonialBuildingRiot.jpg'),
        description: `The Colonial Building Riot was an incident where protests on this day in 1932, in St. John's, Newfoundland turned violent, nearly causing the death of the Prime Minister, who promptly resigned. The protests were prompted by the Great Depression and corruption in the government of John Squires, the Newfoundland Prime Minister at that time.\n\nThe crowd of approximately 10,000 protesters were demanding a petition to investigate Squires for corruption, however they became unruly when not receiving a response. Some members of the crowd beat down the doors to the Colonial Building, and, when entering it, the police attacked all protesters, inside and outside the building. In response, protesters began throwing objects through windows and attemped to set the Colonial Building on fire. Prime Minister Squires exited the building, but was found by the crowd, who assaulted him and forced him to shelter at a private residence.\n\nSquires immediately resigned - while the riot was still going on - and called new elections. His party, the Liberal Party, won only two seats, with the vast majority going to the United Newfoundland Party. Regardless, this government was dissolved in 1934 and replaced by the Commission of Government, a non-democratic body with representatives chosen directly by the British Government.`,
