        date: 'May 5th, 1893',
        title: 'Farabundo Martí (1893 - 1931)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Individuals/farabundoMarti.jpg'),
        description: `Agustín Farabundo Martí Rodríguez, born on this day in 1893, was a Marxist-Leninist activist and a revolutionary leader in El Salvador during the 1932 Salvadoran peasant massacre known as "La Matanza". Martí is also known for co-founding of the Communist Party of Central America, as well as helping lead a communist alternative to the Red Cross known as "International Red Aid".\n\nIn 1931, Martí returned to El Salvador and helped start a guerrilla revolt of indigenous farmers. The Communist-led peasant uprising against dictator Maximiliano Hernández Martínez, fomented by collapsing coffee prices, enjoyed some initial success, but was soon drowned in a bloodbath, being crushed by the Salvadoran military ten days after it had begun. Over 30,000 indigenous people were killed at what was to be a "peaceful meeting" in 1932; this became known as "La Matanza" ("The Slaughter").\n\nFor his role in the uprising, Martí was executed by Salvadoran President Hernández Martínez.`,
