        title: 'U.S. Annexes Hawaii (1898)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/hawaiiAnnexed.jpg'),
        description: `On January 17th, 1893, Queen Liliʻuokalani was overthrown by a group of predominantly foreign insurgents who sought American annexation of the Hawaiian islands. They successfully requested assistance from the U.S. government, who sent 162 sailors to occupy Oahu.\n\nOn this day in 1898, a formal ceremony at Iolani Palace was held to commemorate the annexation. Most of the 40,000 Native Hawaiians, including Liliʻuokalani and the royal family, shuttered themselves in their homes, protesting against what they considered an illegal transaction.\n\nThe revolution and subsequent annexation of Hawaii was the beginning of a long period of expansionism from the United States. Just three years later, the U.S. refused to withdraw troops from Cuba until their government ratified the Platt Amendment, which let Cuba only have "independence" under de facto American hegemony.`,
