        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/marikanaMassacre.jpeg'),
        description: `On this day in 2012, The Marikana massacre took place in South Africa. It was the most lethal use of force by South African security forces against civilians since 1976. The shootings have been compared to the infamous Sharpeville massacre in 1960 (also another instance of police firing on crowds in South Africa). The incident took place on the 25-year anniversary of a nationwide strike by over 300,000 South African Miners.\n\nThe Marikana massacre began as a wildcat strike at a mine owned by Lonmin in the Marikana area, close to Rustenburg, South Africa. Although ten people (mostly workers) had been killed before August 16th, it was on that day that an elite force from the South African Police Service fired into a crowd of strikers with assault rifles, killing 34 injuring 76 were injured.\n\nAfter surveying the aftermath of the violence, photojournalist Greg Marinovich concluded that "[it is clear] that heavily armed police hunted down and killed the miners in cold blood." A year after it occurred, author Benjamin Fogel wrote "Perhaps the most important lesson of Marikana is that the state can gun down dozens of black workers with little or no backlash from 'civil society', the judicial system or from within the institutions that supposedly form the bedrock of democracy."`,
        link: 'https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/19/marikana-massacre-untold-story-strike-leader-died-workers-rights',
