        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/mobileBreadRiot.jpg'),
        description: `The Mobile Bread Riot, which occurred on this day in 1863, was one of several bread riots that took place in the South during the Civil War. The riot was culmination of rising prices and food shortages caused by the Union's naval blockade of Mobile Bay and Confederate general John C. Pemberton's order to not let any corn leave the state of Mississippi.\n\nThe scale of inflation was staggering - molasses, which before the war sold for less than $.30 per gallon, rose to $7.00 per gallon; the cost of a barrel of flour rose from $44.00 to more than $400.00. On this day, hundreds of rioters took to the streets, chanting "Bread or blood!", looting stores and destroying property.\n\nNotably, Confederate general Dabney H. Maury dispatched the Seventeenth Alabama Regiment to quell the riot, but the soldiers refused to intervene.`,
