        title: 'Étaples Mutiny (1917)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/etaplesMutiny.jpg'),
        description: `The Étaples Mutiny was a series of mutinies that began on this day in 1917, committed by British Army and British Imperial soldiers in the coastal port of Étaples in Northern France during World War I.\n\nThe soldiers were enrolled in a training camp there, and on the other side of the river was the smart beach resort known officially as "Le Touquet-Paris-Plage". Le Touquet was, in effect, officers' territory, and pickets were stationed on the bridge over the Canche to enforce this.\n\nOn this day in 1917, Gunner A. J. Healy, who had been walking along the river at low tide, returned across the bridge and was apprehended by those pickets and accused of being a deserter. Upon hearing this, angry soldiers from the camp formed an angry mob and moved towards the town, failing to disperse, even after being told that Healy had been released. His arrest was merely catalyst for open rebellion after years of soldiers' discontent.\n\nThe crowd of soldiers clashed with police, who shot openly into the crowd. Open mutiny continued for days before being put down by force and mass arrests on September 12th. Corporal Jesse Short convicted of attempted mutiny and executed by firing squad. Many other soldiers received lesser punishments, ranging from demotion in rank and fines to as many as ten years in prison.`,
