        category: 'Rebellion',
        date: 'December 5th, 1955',
        title: 'Montgomery Bus Boycott Begins (1955)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Events/busBoycott.jpg'),
        description: `The Montgomery Bus Boycott was a city-wide boycott of the bus system for its racist policies that began on this day in 1955, just 4 days after Rosa Parks was arrested for refusing to give up her seat on the bus for a white man. The leader of the local NAACP chapter, E.D. Nixon, used her arrest to launch a bus boycott to try and change the city's bus policies.\n\nThe boycott had widespread support in the black community, and black taxi drivers lowered their fares to match the cost of taking a bus in solidarity. In response, the membership of the "White Citizen's Council" increased dramatically.\n\nMany acts of terrorism were committed by whites in response to the boycott - the homes of Martin Luther King Jr. and Ralph Abernathy were firebombed, boycotters were often physically attacked, and dozens of activists were arrested.\n\nThe boycott ended on December 20th of 1956, when the city passed an ordinance allowing black members to sit where they wanted on the bus. The campaign of white terrorism continued, however, and all within the month that followed integration on buses, multiple churches were bombed, buses were subject to sniper fire, and at least one black man was lynched.`,
        link: 'https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/montgomery-bus-boycott-1955-56/',
