        title: 'Thomas Mooney (1882 - 1942)',
        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Individuals/thomasMooney.jpg'),
        description: `Thomas Joseph Mooney, born on this day in 1882, was an American political activist and labor leader who is most well-known for being convicted of the San Francisco Preparedness Day Bombing of 1916.\n\nMooney was well-known as a socialist and labor radical - he assisted Eugene V. Debs's 1910 presidential campaign, published socialist literature, and was a member of the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW). After the Preparedness Day Bombing, Mooney, his wife Rena, and two associates were arrested and subjected to a show trial.\n\nConvicted on scant evidence, Mooney served 22 years in prison before finally being pardoned in 1939. Mooney then campaigned for his associate Warren Billings's release, traveling around the country making speeches. He drew a full house at Madison Square Garden in New York City. Billings was released in 1939 and pardoned in 1961.`,
