        imgSrc: require('./assets/eventPhotos/Individuals/maoZedong.jpg'),
        description: `Mao Zedong, born on this day in 1893, was a communist revolutionary who was a founder of the People's Republic of China, which he governed as the chairman of the Communist Party of China from 1949 until his death in 1976. Making his own innovations on Marxism-Leninism, his theories, military strategies, and political policies are collectively known as Maoism.\n\nSeveral monumental events in Chinese history occurred while he was in power, such as the Great Leap Forward, the Cultural Revolution, Chinese involvement in both the Korean War and the Vietnam War, the Sino-Soviet split, and Richard Nixon's 1972 diplomatic visit to Beijing.\n\nMao's legacy remains polarizing for the political left. Supporters credit him with driving imperialism out of China, modernizing the nation and building it into a world power, promoting the status of women, improving education and healthcare, and ultimately increasing the life expectancy of the average Chinese citizen.\n\nMao's critics hold him responsible for widespread political repression and violence, the Great Chinese Famine that occurred as part of agricultural collectivization, and the destruction of many cultural sites and artifacts during the Cultural Revolution.\n\n"Marxism comprises many principles, but in the final analysis they can all be brought back to a single sentence: it is right to rebel against reactionaries." - Mao Zedong`,
